{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511627"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:44:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11771"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11771"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.33,0.01,0.19,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4384"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4384"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96808"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4159"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48428"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of crampy abdominal pain and vomiting. She has not passed flatus for 24 hours. Five years ago, she underwent an open appendicectomy. On examination, her abdomen is distended and soft with high-pitched bowel sounds. A plain X-ray of her abdomen is shown (Image). Intravenous fluid replacement is given, and nasogastric aspiration is started. Two days later, her condition remains unchanged, with no evidence of relief of the obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current management","Gastrografin study","IV antibiotics","CT abdomen with contrast","Surgical exploration"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has small bowel obstruction, likely due to adhesions from her previous appendicectomy. Most cases of adhesive obstruction resolve with conservative management, including gut rest and intravenous fluids, typically within one or two days of hospital admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven that the patient has been treated conservatively for 48 hours without resolution, a \u003Cstrong\u003EGastrografin study\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This involves administering a water-soluble oral contrast agent and assessing its passage through the gastrointestinal tract. If the contrast does not reach the colon within 24 hours, it suggests a failure of non-operative management, indicating the need for surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing current management\u003C/strong\u003E would only delay necessary intervention and increase the risk of complications such as bowel ischemia. It is not appropriate given the lack of improvement after 48 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in this scenario as there is no evidence of infection or peritonitis. Antibiotics would be considered if there were signs of bowel perforation or sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for initial assessment to identify the site and cause of obstruction. However, in this case, the likely cause is adhesions, and a CT scan would not change the immediate management plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is considered if the Gastrografin study indicates failure of conservative management or if there are signs of bowel ischemia or perforation. It is not the immediate next step without further diagnostic information from the Gastrografin study.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of adhesive-obstruction will resolve with conservative management.","A Gastrografin study can help determine the need for surgical intervention in unresolved small bowel obstruction.","Adhesive small bowel obstruction is a common complication following abdominal surgery."],"references":["Catena F, De Simone B, Coccolini F, Di Saverio S, Sartelli M, Ansaloni L. Bowel obstruction: a narrative review for all physicians. World J Emerg Surg. 2019 Apr 29;14:20. doi: 10.1186/s13017-019-0240-7. PMID: 31168315; PMCID: PMC6489175. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31168315/","Ishizuka M, Shibuya N, Takagi K, Iwasaki Y, Hachiya H, Aoki T, Kubota K. Gastrografin reduces the need for additional surgery in postoperative small bowel obstruction patients without long tube insertion: A meta-analysis. Ann Gastroenterol Surg. 2018 Dec 17;3(2):187-194. doi: 10.1002/ags3.12223. PMID: 30923788; PMCID: PMC6422814. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30923788/","Biondo S, Par\u00e9s D, Mora L, Mart\u00ed Ragu\u00e9 J, Kreisler E, Jaurrieta E. Randomized clinical study of Gastrografin administration in patients with adhesive small bowel obstruction. Br J Surg. 2003 May;90(5):542-6. doi: 10.1002/bjs.4150. PMID: 12734858. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12734858/","D\u0027Agostino R, Ali NS, Leshchinskiy S, Cherukuri AR, Tam JK. Small bowel obstruction and the gastrografin challenge. Abdom Radiol (NY). 2018 Nov;43(11):2945-2954. doi: 10.1007/s00261-018-1591-3. PMID: 29632988. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29632988/","Soni S, Prakash S, Rai S, et al. Therapeutic use of oral gastrografin in treating acute adhesive small bowel obstruction. Bioinformation 2024; 20: 1447-452."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96808"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17557"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17557"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e7d8bb3a-700c-4258-bfa7-3843f0ade6f7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e7d8bb3a-700c-4258-bfa7-3843f0ade6f7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":330,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96808"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T14:39:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T14:41:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4384"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114805"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings",